<CENTER>
<H1>&nbsp;</H1>
<H1>Colored Petri Nets</H1>
</CENTER>

<UL><UL><UL> <UL><UL><UL>
  <LI><FONT size=5><FONT 
            color=mediumblue><STRONG>Tokens often represent objects (e.g. 
            resources, goods, humans)</STRONG></FONT>    
                in the modeled system</FONT>
  <LI><FONT size=5>To 
            represent attributes of these objects, the Petri net model is 
            extended with coloured or typed tokens: <FONT 
            color=mediumblue><STRONG>each token has a value often referred to as 
            `color'</STRONG></FONT>    
                       
                       
            .</FONT>
  <LI><FONT size=5><FONT 
            color=mediumblue><STRONG>Transitions</STRONG></FONT> use the values 
            of the consumed tokens to <FONT color=mediumblue><STRONG>determine 
            the values of the produced tokens</STRONG></FONT>       
                    : transition describes the relation 
            between the values of the `input tokens' and the values of the 
            `output tokens'.</FONT>
  <LI><FONT size=5>It is 
            also possible to specify `<FONT 
            color=mediumblue><STRONG>preconditions</STRONG></FONT>      
            ' which take the colors of tokens to be consumed into 
            account.</FONT></LI>
</UL></UL></UL></UL></UL></UL>

</BODY></HTML>